&lt;/ul&gt;</content><author><name></name></author><summary type="html">互いに素 def</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Welcome to Jekyll!</title><link href="http://0.0.0.0:4000/jekyll/update/2017/09/06/welcome-to-jekyll.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Welcome to Jekyll!" /><published>2017-09-06T11:02:57-05:00</published><updated>2017-09-06T11:02:57-05:00</updated><id>http://0.0.0.0:4000/jekyll/update/2017/09/06/welcome-to-jekyll</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://0.0.0.0:4000/jekyll/update/2017/09/06/welcome-to-jekyll.html">&lt;p&gt;You’ll find this post in your &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;_posts&lt;/code&gt; directory. Go ahead and edit it and re-build the site to see your changes. You can rebuild the site in many different ways, but the most common way is to run &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;jekyll serve&lt;/code&gt;, which launches a web server and auto-regenerates your site when a file is updated.&lt;/p&gt;

